data.name: ChkSuperstartAutoUpdate.ToolTip
data.value:
Imediatly update the server software when an update is available.
Note: the server won't start until the download has finished, this time depends on your internet speed. This option can't be combined with the notify feature.
IMPORTANT: this is NOT supported by vanilla servers! Vanilla servers will fail to start if this option is enabled.

data.name: ChkSuperstartAutoUpdateNotify.ToolTip
data.value:
Show a dialog that prompts to update when an update is available. Note: the server won't start until the dialog has been closed. This option can't be combined with the auto-update feature.
IMPORTANT: this is NOT supported by vanilla servers! Vanilla servers will fail to start if this option is enabled.

data.name: TxtSuperstartJavaCustomSwitch.ToolTip
data.value: Only for expierienced users. Custom arguments, this is for the server file. Example: All command line arguments, like -port="25565" for the server. The GUI will run java as following (simplified): java.exe [memory settings] [custom arguments] -jar [jar file] [custom switches]

data.name: TxtSuperstartJavaCustomArgs.ToolTip
data.value: Only for expierienced users. Custom arguments, this is for java. Example: All java arguments starting with -xx The GUI will run java as following (simplified): java.exe [memory settings] [custom arguments] -jar [jar file] [custom switches]

data.name: CBSuperstartServerType.ToolTip
data.value:
The server type that you're running.
Bukkit: Bukkit and all servers that are based on bukkit (Spout, Spigot, ...) Vanilla: The vanilla (official) server and everything based on vanilla (Tekkit classic, Voltz, ...) Remote: To connect to a server running on another computer Generic java: This allows you to run any java server. You'll have to enter all the arguments and switches by yourself, only the RAM settings will be set by the GUI.
In case you're expieriencing problems, try swapping between the different server types.

data.name: CBInfoSettingsFileLocation.ToolTip
data.value: Select where the config files of the GUI should be stored. Appdata means that, no matter where you put the executable, the same settings will be used. Recommended. Local means that the config files will be stored in the same folder as the GUI. This is needed to run multiple GUI instances at one computer.
